sorry, looks like i was not clear enough :) the flow i mentioned is about our DC spec (Seed object, not the cloud API). what you described is correct at the openstack API level, but at the moment KKP's stored contract is 1 OS -> 1 image, so there's a discrepancy between what openstack actually has and what KKP stores.

your proposal (kubevirt-style OS -> version -> image in the DC spec) is the cleanest and most correct one, no argument there. the reason i'm hesitant is the cost. we can't reshape images from map[string]string to map[string]map[string]string in place, that's breaking. we'd add a new optional field (e.g. imagesWithVersions) next to the existing one, keep both, and define which wins when both are set.
the field itself is cheap, but the real cost is the permanent two-field precedence logic across three places: frontend default, dashboard API, and the KKP defaulting code in CompleteOpenstackProviderSpec. so it's a real change touching multiple repos, not just one struct field.
So, my concern is most likely related to maintainability cost based on the importance of this support ticket.



Q2: Not sure why do we need this kubermaticsettings thing? I think in any case we need to fetch the list (in case we opt new endpoint) and user has to provide that image in any case otherwise cluster won't be allowed to be created?

To gate this behaviour actually. if someone with openstack doesn't use their image registry often, or doesn't want their KKP user-cluster customers to see everything in the project, they can continue as-is. but if someone wants this new feature, they enable it. i figured kubermaticsettings is a good fit since this is a dashboard API feature, not a core KKP controller thing.
Also, small note on the second part, today the user doesn't strictly have to provide an image. if they leave it empty, KKP defaults it from dc.spec.openstack.images[os] via CompleteOpenstackProviderSpec so the field is more about discoverability than about making the image mandatory. Also, under the hood, machine-controller also runs discovery for os image as well just in case.
